                        <h1>Aerodynamic Aid</h1>
                        <p xmlns="">Aerodynamics are a hugely significant element of motorsports, and are often the largest area of competitive differentiation. They are fundamental to the race car&rsquo;s performance and while the exterior of the car tends to grab all the attention, the choice of engine oil can also have a major influence on the aerodynamic performance.</p>

                        <p xmlns="">One thing aerodynamicists are constantly trying to do is reduce drag losses and increase downforce on the car. Simultaneously, the engine designers work to increase power from the engine, which generates more heat. For that reason, a trade-off is needed as keeping the engine cool requires radiators, but larger radiators increase weight, drag and reduce down-force. In the case of a Grand Prix car, this can account for as much as 15% of the overall drag on the car.</p>

                        <p xmlns="">Mobil 1&trade; lubricant technology, combined with the radiator design, is responsible for an almost equal share of the engine cooling requirement on a Grand Prix car. The Mobil 1 engine oil flows through the radiator, cooling the engine down by approximately 40°C (104°F), whilst the air channelled through the side pod inlet heats up about 75°C (167°F).</p>

                        <p xmlns="">Our engineers push to increase the temperature at which the engine oil is capable of running and there are several advantages of being able to run the engine hotter. Drag can be reduced by re-optimization of the radiator and aero packaging. Increased rear downforce can also be achieved through aerodynamic improvements to the exit ducts.</p>

                        <p xmlns="">There are certainly huge advantages to be gained in being able to improve the car's thermodynamic efficiency and oil that allows the engine to run hotter ultimately leads to better lap times, increased down force and reduced drag proving the benefits of oil as an aerodynamic aid are key to a successful performance.</p>
